{
  "Who is considered the 'father of modern genetics' for his pioneering work on inheritance in the 1860s?": "",
  "Gregor Mendel": "",
  "Charles Darwin": "",
  "Robert Hooke": "",
  "Louis Pasteur": "",
  "Gregor Mendel, an Augustinian friar, conducted groundbreaking experiments on pea plants in the 1860s that established the fundamental laws of inheritance. His work on how traits are passed from parents to offspring earned him the title 'father of modern genetics.' Charles Darwin is known for the theory of evolution, Louis Pasteur for microbiology and pasteurization, and Robert Hooke for coining the term 'cell.'": "",
  "What organism did Mendel use for his famous genetics experiments?": "",
  "Pea plants (Pisum sativum)": "",
  "Corn plants (Zea mays)": "",
  "Fruit flies (Drosophila melanogaster)": "",
  "Bacteria (Escherichia coli)": "",
  "Mendel used garden pea plants (Pisum sativum) because they had clearly contrasting traits (tall/short, yellow/green seeds, round/wrinkled seeds), short generation times, large numbers of offspring, and could be easily cross-pollinated or self-pollinated. Fruit flies (Drosophila) became a model genetics organism later through Thomas Hunt Morgan's work in the early 1900s.": "",
  "In a heterozygous organism, what does the dominant allele do to the recessive allele's expression?": "",
  "It has no effect — both alleles are expressed equally": "",
  "It permanently deletes the recessive allele from the DNA": "",
  "It masks the expression of the recessive allele so only the dominant trait is observed": "",
  "It blends with the recessive allele to produce an intermediate trait": "",
  "In a heterozygous organism (e.g., Tt), the dominant allele masks the expression of the recessive allele, meaning only the dominant phenotype is observed. The recessive allele is still present in the genotype — it is not deleted or altered — it simply is not expressed when a dominant allele is present. Blending inheritance was disproven by Mendel's experiments, which showed traits remain discrete.": "",
  "When is a recessive trait expressed in an organism's phenotype?": "",
  "Only in the F1 generation of a cross": "",
  "Only when the organism is homozygous recessive (e.g., tt)": "",
  "Whenever at least one recessive allele is present": "",
  "Recessive traits are never expressed in any organism": "",
  "A recessive trait is only visible in the phenotype when the organism has two copies of the recessive allele (homozygous recessive, e.g., tt). In a heterozygous organism (Tt), the dominant allele masks the recessive one. Having just one recessive allele is not enough for expression under complete dominance. Recessive traits can appear in any generation — they famously 'skip' the F1 and reappear in the F2 in Mendel's classic crosses.": "",
  "How many alleles for a single gene does a diploid organism inherit, and from whom?": "",
  "It varies depending on the trait": "",
  "Four alleles — two from each parent": "",
  "One allele — from the dominant parent only": "",
  "Two alleles — one from each parent": "",
  "For each gene, a diploid organism inherits exactly two alleles — one from the mother and one from the father. These two alleles make up the organism's genotype for that trait (e.g., TT, Tt, or tt). This is a consequence of meiosis, where each gamete carries only one allele per gene, and fertilization restores the pair. The number of alleles per gene does not vary by trait in diploid organisms.": "",
  "What does it mean when an organism is described as 'true-breeding' for a trait?": "",
  "It always produces offspring identical to itself for that trait when self-pollinated, because it is homozygous": "",
  "It can only produce one offspring per generation": "",
  "It has been genetically modified in a laboratory": "",
  "It shows a blended phenotype from both parents": "",
  "True-breeding organisms are homozygous for a trait (e.g., TT or tt). When they self-pollinate or mate with an identical genotype, all offspring have the same phenotype as the parents. Mendel established true-breeding lines (P generation) before performing his crosses to ensure a clean experimental starting point. Heterozygous organisms (Tt) would produce mixed offspring when self-pollinated, so they are not true-breeding.": "",
  "In genetics notation, the offspring of the P (parental) generation are designated as which generation?": "",
  "P2 (second parental generation)": "",
  "F0 (zeroth filial generation)": "",
  "G1 (first genetic generation)": "",
  "F1 (first filial generation)": "",
  "In genetics notation, the P generation refers to the parental generation. Their offspring are called the F1 (first filial) generation, from the Latin 'filius' meaning son. The offspring of the F1 generation are the F2 (second filial) generation, and so on. There is no P2, F0, or G1 designation in standard genetics nomenclature.": "",
  "What tool is used to predict the possible genotypes and phenotypes of offspring from a genetic cross?": "",
  "A Punnett square": "",
  "A karyotype": "",
  "A gel electrophoresis apparatus": "",
  "A pedigree chart": "",
  "A Punnett square is a grid diagram used to predict the probability of offspring genotypes and phenotypes from a genetic cross. One parent's possible gametes are placed along the top and the other's along the side, with each box representing a possible offspring genotype. A karyotype displays an organism's chromosomes, gel electrophoresis separates DNA fragments by size, and a pedigree chart tracks inheritance patterns through family generations.": "",
  "When Mendel crossed true-breeding tall plants (TT) with true-breeding short plants (tt), what phenotype did ALL F1 offspring display?": "",
  "Short — because recessive traits are stronger": "",
  "Medium height — because the alleles blend together": "",
  "Tall — because the dominant allele (T) masks the recessive allele (t)": "",
  "Half were tall and half were short": "",
  "All F1 offspring from TT x tt are heterozygous (Tt). Because tall (T) is dominant over short (t), all F1 plants display the tall phenotype. This demonstrates the principle of dominance — one copy of the dominant allele is sufficient to produce the dominant phenotype. The recessive allele (t) is still present but not expressed. Blending inheritance was disproven by Mendel's experiments.": "",
  "What is the expected phenotypic ratio from a monohybrid cross between two heterozygous organisms (Tt x Tt)?": "",
  "3:1 (three dominant phenotype to one recessive phenotype)": "",
  "All offspring show the dominant phenotype": "",
  "1:1 (equal dominant and recessive)": "",
  "1:2:1 (one dominant, two intermediate, one recessive)": "",
  "A cross of Tt x Tt produces offspring in a 1:2:1 genotypic ratio (1 TT : 2 Tt : 1 tt). Under complete dominance, both TT and Tt show the dominant phenotype, giving a 3:1 phenotypic ratio (3 dominant : 1 recessive). The 1:2:1 is the genotypic ratio, not the phenotypic ratio. A 1:1 ratio results from Tt x tt. 'All dominant' would result from TT x any genotype.": "",
  "Which of the following BEST defines an allele?": "",
  "A type of protein produced by DNA during translation": "",
  "A complete chromosome inherited from one parent": "",
  "Another name for a gene — the terms are interchangeable": "",
  "An alternative form of a gene that occupies the same position (locus) on a chromosome": "",
  "An allele is one of two or more alternative versions of a gene found at the same locus (position) on a chromosome. For example, the gene for pea plant height has two alleles: T (tall) and t (short). Each diploid organism inherits two alleles per gene — one from each parent. Alleles are not proteins, not whole chromosomes, and while related to genes, the terms are not interchangeable — a gene can have multiple alleles.": "",
  "Which of the following BEST describes what it means for a trait to be dominant?": "",
  "The trait is always the most common phenotype in a population": "",
  "The trait will eventually replace the recessive trait over many generations": "",
  "The trait requires two copies of the allele to be expressed": "",
  "The trait is expressed in the phenotype when at least one dominant allele is present": "",
  "A dominant trait is expressed whenever at least one copy of the dominant allele is present (in both homozygous dominant and heterozygous individuals). Dominance does NOT mean the trait is more common in a population — a recessive trait can be more frequent if natural selection favors it. Dominant alleles do not replace recessive ones over time. Requiring two copies for expression describes a recessive trait, not a dominant one.": "",
  "Which of the following BEST describes what it means for a trait to be recessive?": "",
  "The trait can never be passed to offspring if a parent is unaffected": "",
  "The trait is only expressed when two copies of the recessive allele are present (homozygous recessive)": "",
  "The trait is always harmful or causes genetic disorders": "",
  "The trait will disappear from the population over time through natural selection": "",
  "A recessive trait requires two copies of the recessive allele (homozygous recessive, e.g., tt) to be expressed in the phenotype. In heterozygous individuals, the recessive allele is present but masked by the dominant allele. Recessive traits do not disappear from populations — they can be carried silently by heterozygous carriers for many generations. Recessive traits are not inherently harmful (e.g., blue eyes and straight hair are recessive traits).": "",
  "Which of the following BEST defines genotype?": "",
  "The specific combination of alleles an organism carries for a particular trait (e.g., TT, Tt, or tt)": "",
  "The process by which genes are converted into functional proteins": "",
  "The total number of chromosomes found in a cell": "",
  "The physical appearance or observable characteristics of an organism": "",
  "Genotype refers to the genetic makeup of an organism for a specific trait, expressed as allele combinations like TT (homozygous dominant), Tt (heterozygous), or tt (homozygous recessive). It represents what alleles are present in the DNA. The physical appearance is the phenotype, not the genotype. The chromosome count is called ploidy, and converting genes to proteins is gene expression.": "",
  "Which of the following BEST defines phenotype?": "",
  "The observable physical characteristics of an organism resulting from its genotype and environment": "",
  "A type of genetic mutation that alters DNA sequence": "",
  "The sequence of nucleotides in a gene": "",
  "The specific allele combination an organism carries for a trait": "",
  "Phenotype refers to the observable traits of an organism — such as height, color, shape, or behavior — that result from the interaction between its genotype and environmental factors. For example, a plant with genotype Tt has a tall phenotype under complete dominance. The allele combination is the genotype, not the phenotype. Phenotype is not a mutation, and it is not the DNA sequence itself.": "",
  "What does the term 'homozygous' mean in genetics?": "",
  "Having alleles located on different chromosomes": "",
  "Having two identical alleles for a particular gene (e.g., TT or tt)": "",
  "Having two different alleles for a particular gene": "",
  "Having only one allele for a gene instead of two": "",
  "Homozygous means an organism has two identical alleles at a particular gene locus — either homozygous dominant (TT) or homozygous recessive (tt). True-breeding organisms are homozygous for the traits they breed true for. Having two different alleles (e.g., Tt) is called heterozygous. All diploid organisms have two alleles per gene, located at the same locus on homologous chromosomes.": "",
  "What does the term 'heterozygous' mean in genetics?": "",
  "Having no alleles for a particular gene": "",
  "Having two identical alleles for a particular gene": "",
  "Having alleles inherited from only one parent": "",
  "Having two different alleles for a particular gene (e.g., Tt)": "",
  "Heterozygous means an organism carries two different alleles at a gene locus — for example, Tt for the height gene, with one dominant (T) and one recessive (t) allele. In Mendel's crosses, the F1 generation from TT x tt are all heterozygous (Tt). Heterozygous individuals are sometimes called 'carriers' for recessive traits because they carry the recessive allele without expressing it. Having two identical alleles is homozygous.": "",
  "What is the purpose of a Punnett square in genetics?": "",
  "To graph changes in allele frequencies in a population over time": "",
  "To predict the genotype and phenotype probabilities of offspring from a specific genetic cross": "",
  "To measure the physical size of individual chromosomes": "",
  "To display a list of all known human genetic disorders": "",
  "A Punnett square is a grid diagram named after Reginald Punnett. One parent's possible gametes are placed across the top and the other parent's along the side. Each cell in the grid shows a possible offspring genotype. For a monohybrid cross (e.g., Tt x Tt), a 2x2 grid with 4 boxes is used. For a dihybrid cross (e.g., TtYy x TtYy), a 4x4 grid with 16 boxes is used.": "",
  "Which of the following BEST states Mendel's Law of Segregation?": "",
  "Organisms always segregate into purely dominant and purely recessive groups": "",
  "During gamete formation, the two alleles for each gene separate so that each gamete carries only one allele": "",
  "Dominant alleles segregate into different cells than recessive alleles during meiosis": "",
  "Genes located on the same chromosome always stay together during cell division": "",
  "Mendel's Law of Segregation states that during meiosis, the two alleles for each gene separate (segregate) into different gametes, so each gamete carries only one allele for each trait. When fertilization occurs, the offspring receives one allele from each parent, restoring the pair. This law explains the 3:1 phenotypic ratio observed in monohybrid crosses between heterozygotes (Tt x Tt). Alleles segregate randomly — dominant and recessive alleles do not sort into separate cells preferentially.": "",
  "Which of the following BEST states Mendel's Law of Independent Assortment?": "",
  "Genes on the same chromosome always assort independently of each other": "",
  "Offspring always display the same trait combinations as their parents": "",
  "Genes for different traits on separate chromosomes are inherited independently of one another during gamete formation": "",
  "All genes in an organism are inherited together as a single unit": "",
  "Mendel's Law of Independent Assortment states that alleles of different genes assort independently during gamete formation, provided they are located on different chromosomes. The inheritance of one trait does not affect the inheritance of another. This law explains the 9:3:3:1 phenotypic ratio in dihybrid crosses (e.g., RrYy x RrYy). An important exception is genetic linkage — genes on the SAME chromosome that are close together tend to be inherited as a unit and do NOT assort independently.": "",
  "Two heterozygous tall pea plants (Tt x Tt) are crossed. Using a Punnett square, what is the probability that a single offspring will be homozygous recessive (tt) and therefore short?": "",
  "75% (3 out of 4 possible outcomes)": "",
  "50% (2 out of 4 possible outcomes)": "",
  "25% (1 out of 4 possible outcomes)": "",
  "0% — it is impossible when both parents are tall": "",
  "Setting up a Punnett square for Tt x Tt yields four equally likely outcomes: TT (25%), Tt (25%), Tt (25%), and tt (25%). Only 1 out of 4 boxes is tt, so the probability of a homozygous recessive offspring is 25%. The 50% answer confuses the probability of getting 't' from one parent with getting 'tt' from both. Both parents carry a recessive allele, so producing a tt offspring is certainly possible — just not guaranteed.": "",
  "A brown-eyed man (Bb) marries a blue-eyed woman (bb). Blue eyes are recessive. What is the expected phenotypic ratio among their children?": "",
  "1 brown-eyed : 1 blue-eyed (50% each)": "",
  "All blue-eyed": "",
  "3 brown-eyed : 1 blue-eyed": "",
  "All brown-eyed": "",
  "For Bb x bb: the father can pass B or b (50% each), and the mother can only pass b. Offspring are either Bb (brown eyes, 50%) or bb (blue eyes, 50%), giving a 1:1 phenotypic ratio. The 3:1 ratio comes from a cross between two heterozygotes (Bb x Bb), not this cross. Not all children will be brown-eyed because the father passes his 'b' allele to half his children, and the mother always contributes 'b.'": "",
  "A plant breeder has a purple-flowered pea plant but does not know if it is PP or Pp. She crosses it with a white-flowered plant (pp) and all 40 offspring have purple flowers. What can she most likely conclude about the purple parent's genotype?": "",
  "White flowers are not actually recessive in this species": "",
  "The purple parent is most likely homozygous dominant (PP), because no recessive phenotype appeared among many offspring": "",
  "The purple parent must be Pp because some offspring could still be white in the future": "",
  "The test is completely inconclusive regardless of how many offspring are produced": "",
  "This is a test cross — crossing an organism of unknown genotype with a homozygous recessive (pp). If the purple parent were Pp, approximately 50% of offspring would be pp (white). With 40 offspring all showing purple flowers, the probability that the parent is Pp is astronomically low (0.5^40). The parent is almost certainly PP. While absolute proof requires genetic sequencing, 40 offspring with no recessive phenotype is very strong statistical evidence.": "",
  "In a dihybrid cross between two organisms heterozygous for both traits (RrYy x RrYy), what is the expected phenotypic ratio in the offspring?": "",
  "9:3:3:1 (9 both dominant : 3 first dominant only : 3 second dominant only : 1 both recessive)": "",
  "3:1 (three dominant to one recessive)": "",
  "1:1:1:1 (equal proportions of all four phenotypes)": "",
  "A dihybrid cross between two double heterozygotes (RrYy x RrYy) involves a 4x4 Punnett square with 16 possible outcomes. The phenotypic ratio under complete dominance is 9:3:3:1 — 9 showing both dominant traits, 3 showing only the first dominant trait, 3 showing only the second dominant trait, and 1 showing both recessive traits. The 3:1 ratio applies only to monohybrid crosses. The 1:1:1:1 ratio would come from a dihybrid test cross (RrYy x rryy).": "",
  "Two parents are both carriers of sickle cell trait (Ss x Ss), where S is the normal hemoglobin allele and s is the sickle cell allele. What is the probability their child will have sickle cell disease (ss)?": "",
  "75% — most children will be affected since both parents carry the allele": "",
  "50% — half the children will be affected": "",
  "25% — there is a 1 in 4 chance the child inherits 's' from both parents": "",
  "0% — because both parents are healthy, no child can be affected": "",
  "For Ss x Ss, the Punnett square yields: SS (25%), Ss (25%), Ss (25%), ss (25%). The probability of having sickle cell disease (ss) is 1/4 or 25%. Each parent has a 50% chance of passing the 's' allele, and the probability of BOTH passing 's' simultaneously is 0.5 x 0.5 = 0.25 (25%). Even though both parents appear healthy, they each silently carry one copy of the recessive allele, making affected offspring possible.": "",
  "In a family, neither parent has cystic fibrosis (a recessive condition), yet their child is diagnosed with it. How is this possible according to Mendelian genetics?": "",
  "The child must have developed a new spontaneous mutation not present in either parent": "",
  "Both parents are heterozygous carriers (Cc) who each passed their recessive allele (c) to the child, making the child cc": "",
  "One parent must secretly have cystic fibrosis but was misdiagnosed": "",
  "This is impossible — recessive traits cannot skip generations": "",
  "This is a classic example of autosomal recessive inheritance. Both parents are carriers (Cc) — they each carry one copy of the recessive allele without showing symptoms because the dominant allele masks it. When both parents pass the 'c' allele to their child, the child is cc and has cystic fibrosis. This demonstrates how recessive traits can 'skip' generations — they hide in heterozygous carriers. From Cc x Cc, there is a 25% chance of an affected child in each pregnancy.": "",
  "A cross between a black rabbit and a white rabbit produces approximately half black and half white offspring. Black fur (B) is dominant over white fur (b). What are the most likely genotypes of the parents?": "",
  "The black parent is Bb (heterozygous) and the white parent is bb (homozygous recessive)": "",
  "The black parent is BB (homozygous dominant) and the white parent is bb": "",
  "Both parents are bb (homozygous recessive)": "",
  "Both parents are Bb (heterozygous), producing a 3:1 ratio": "",
  "An approximately 1:1 ratio of black to white offspring indicates a test cross: Bb x bb. The heterozygous black parent contributes B or b with equal probability, and the homozygous recessive white parent only contributes b. This gives Bb (black, 50%) and bb (white, 50%) offspring. If the black parent were BB, ALL offspring would be Bb (black). A Bb x Bb cross would produce a 3:1 ratio, not 1:1. Both parents cannot be bb because black offspring were produced.": "",
  "In pea plants, round seeds (R) are dominant over wrinkled (r) and yellow seeds (Y) are dominant over green (y). Using the multiplication rule, what is the probability of getting a wrinkled, green offspring (rryy) from the cross RrYy x RrYy?": "",
  "9/16 — because the dominant phenotype combination is most common": "",
  "1/2 — because there are only two possible phenotypes per trait": "",
  "1/4 — because each recessive trait has a 1/4 chance": "",
  "1/16 — because P(rr) = 1/4 and P(yy) = 1/4, and 1/4 x 1/4 = 1/16": "",
  "The multiplication rule works because the two genes assort independently. The probability of rr from Rr x Rr is 1/4, and the probability of yy from Yy x Yy is also 1/4. Since the events are independent: 1/4 x 1/4 = 1/16. This corresponds to the '1' in the 9:3:3:1 ratio. The 1/4 answer only accounts for one gene, not both. The 9/16 represents the double dominant class (round yellow), not the double recessive.": "",
  "A genetic counselor examines a pedigree chart and notices that an autosomal recessive disorder appears in grandchildren but not in the parents or grandparents (the trait seems to skip a generation). Which inheritance pattern best explains this observation?": "",
  "Autosomal recessive — unaffected parents who are heterozygous carriers can produce affected offspring": "",
  "Mitochondrial inheritance — traits passed exclusively through the mother": "",
  "Autosomal dominant — the trait is simply being masked by environmental factors": "",
  "X-linked recessive — only males are ever affected by this pattern": "",
  "Autosomal recessive traits characteristically 'skip' generations. Unaffected carrier parents (Aa x Aa) have a 25% chance of producing affected children (aa) in each pregnancy. The trait appears to skip because carriers (Aa) do not show the phenotype — the recessive allele is masked by the dominant allele. Autosomal dominant traits typically appear in every generation. X-linked recessive shows a specific pattern affecting mostly males. Mitochondrial inheritance follows the maternal line exclusively.": "",
  "A farmer has two pea plants: one with round, yellow seeds (genotype unknown) and one with wrinkled, green seeds (rryy). He crosses them and ALL offspring have round, yellow seeds. What is the most likely genotype of the round, yellow parent?": "",
  "rrYY (homozygous recessive for shape, homozygous dominant for color)": "",
  "RrYy (heterozygous for both traits), because it shows both dominant phenotypes": "",
  "RRYY (homozygous dominant for both traits), because no recessive phenotypes appeared in any offspring": "",
  "Rryy (heterozygous for shape, homozygous recessive for color)": "",
  "This is a dihybrid test cross. The wrinkled, green parent is rryy and can only contribute r and y alleles to offspring. If the round, yellow parent were RrYy, approximately 1/4 of offspring would show at least one recessive phenotype (wrinkled or green). Since ALL offspring show both dominant traits (round and yellow), the first parent must be contributing only R and Y alleles to every offspring, making it RRYY (homozygous dominant for both genes). The genotype RrYy would produce some wrinkled or green offspring in a large sample.": ""
}